## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** patterns that break on .NET 8:

| Pattern Found | Line | .NET 8 Behavior |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Never thrown â€” cleanup never runs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

The fundamental shift: .NET 8 uses **cooperative cancellation** â€” your code must voluntarily check for and respond to cancellation. The runtime will not forcibly inject exceptions.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work â€” migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort equivalent needed: just let the loop condition
                // re-evaluate. If you want to continue processing remaining items
                // after a per-item cancellation, use a per-item CancellationTokenSource
                // linked to the parent token.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `volatile bool _running` â†’ `CancellationToken`**
The token does the same job but also wakes up blocking calls. Your old `_running` flag couldn't interrupt `GetNextItem()` if it was blocked.

**2. `Thread.Abort()` â†’ `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`**
Signals the token; the loop exits at the next checkpoint or when a blocking call observes the token.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` â†’ `catch (OperationCanceledException)`**
The `when` guard ensures you only catch cancellations from *your* token, not unrelated ones.

**4. `Thread.ResetAbort()` â†’ removed**
Not needed. After catching `OperationCanceledException`, execution continues normally â€” the loop condition re-evaluates and exits.

**5. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` â†’ `Thread.Join(TimeSpan)`**
`Join` actually waits for the thread to finish rather than hoping 2 seconds is enough.

## Critical Pitfall: Blocking Calls

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue or socket), **you must pass the token through**:

```csharp
// âťŚ Old â€” will hang forever, cancellation can't reach it
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks indefinitely
}

// âś… New â€” wakes up when cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If the blocking call doesn't accept a token (e.g., raw socket I/O), replace it with an async overload or use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` polling.

## Common Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Why It Matters |
|---|---|
| Not passing token through the full call chain | Cancellation stalls at the first method that ignores it |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks timers and callbacks |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` without the `when` guard | May swallow unrelated cancellations |
| Assuming cancellation is instant | It only fires at the next checkpoint â€” add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running |
